\cf2 \
Master/disciple pedagogy and transference\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1 \cf3 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}theory relies on "the charismatic persona of the master theorist"; theorists \cf2 can be recognized\cf3  as masters by the fact that they have disciples\cf2  (179)\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1\cf2 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}\cf3 \'93the institutional position of the master theorist, as the person in whom institutional and personal prestige is \'91blended,\'92 and in whom the concept of 'autonomy' is maximally overdetermined, was always a condition for the emergence of theory.\'94 (155)\cf2  \
\ls4\ilvl1
\b \cf3 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}\'93The increasingly technobureaucratic organization of the professional field of literary criticism was a condition for the emergence of theory, which we can understand in retrospect as the reassertion of charismatic authority in the face of that technobureaucratic domination."
\b0  (256)\cf2 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0 \cf2 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \cf3 "If the institutional locus of canon formation is the school, and its instrumentality the syllabus, the social relation between teacher and student oddly effaces its institutional conditions in producing nothing less than a kind of love: first the love of the disciple for the master, and then the love for what the master teaches, his 'teaching,' and beyond that, as we shall see, a love for the very texts the master loves." (182)\cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \cf3 "By transferring the eros of the transference to the lesson, the transference itself will disappear; it will be terminated. ... And this is to say that nothing will remain of de Man in the lesson, that loving the lesson is not, finally, the same as loving de Man." (185)\cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf3 \'93Lacan expresses the problem of psychoanalytic theory's transmission as the thematic of the distinction between science and religion. What the theorist wants (but this is not yet equivalent to the 'desire of the analyst\'92) is the transmission of theory, that is, the solution to a problem in pedagogy. Whether or not a theory carries with it a claim to scientificity, its transmission would be better assured by its organization in the form of a science\'94 (198)\cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\b \cf3 "the transference onto theory always misses its object, the positive content of theory, by cathecting in and behind that object the image of the master.\'94
\b0  (201)\cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}De Man: 
\f1 \cf3 "
\b What de Man gains tactically by reducing all intersubjective relations to the possibility of cognitive (that is, linguistic) error is the total obliteration of the transference from the terrain of the discussion
\b0 ." (193)
\f0 \cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Lacan: 
\f1\b \cf3 Lacan's matheme: \'93By reducing transmission to a rote process the doctrine was supposed to escape a certain contingency of the transference
\b0 , its constitutive ambivalence, its love-hate. But the reception of the matheme marked a greater investment in the transference than ever before, even as both master and disciple deferred to the impersonal form of the algorithm.\'94 (202)
\f0 \cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1 \cf3 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\'93
\b Lacan and de Man appear to set off resolutely on opposite theoretical directions, but ... they end up in the same place, the place of the \'91the subject who is supposed to know.
\b0 \'92\'94 (195)\cf2 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \cf3 \'93
\b the teaching of both de Man and Lacan attempts to account and compensate for the vicissitudes of transmission by attributing those vicissitudes to an epistemological defect of language, or by refusing in principle the possibility of the dissolution of the transference. The two positions amount in practice to the same thing
\b0 ." (202)
\f0 \cf2 \
